In this proclamation, President Donald Trump recognizes September 2020 as National Childhood Cancer Awareness Month. He acknowledges the challenges faced by children and adolescents diagnosed with cancer and expresses commitment to combating pediatric cancers. The administration plans to invest $500 million over the next decade to support research and treatment for childhood cancer. Efforts include the implementation of the Childhood Cancer Data Initiative by the National Cancer Institute and the acceleration of drug development by the Food and Drug Administration's Pediatric Oncology program. The proclamation also honors those who have lost their lives to cancer and encourages support for families battling childhood cancer. It calls upon American citizens, government agencies, businesses, nonprofit organizations, and the media to increase awareness and support for the fight against childhood cancer.